A shematic showing the 3 types of hydrogen is at:
<http://upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/c/c9/Hydrogen_Deuterium_Tritium_Nuclei_Schmatic-de.svg/800px-Hydrogen_Deuterium_Tritium_Nuclei_Schmatic-de.svg.png> where Wasserstoff is the stable hydrogen atom. -
Mod.JW]

[Tritium is a radioactive form of hydrogen, most often associated with
research. As a form of hydrogen, tritium is found naturally in air and
water. Most hydrogen is made up of one proton, and an orbital
electron, but tritium has 2 extra neutrons in the nucleus. As with
anything, the dose makes the poison, and therefore the dose of tritium
is dependent upon how much was initially ingested and the length of
time in the body.

Tritium is produced naturally in the upper atmosphere when cosmic rays
strike nitrogen molecules in the air. Tritium is also produced during
nuclear weapons explosions, as a byproduct in reactors producing
electricity, and in special production reactors, where the isotope
lithium-6 is bombarded to produce tritium.

Tritium is used in some light sources, watches, exit signs, and a
number of other products. Tritium is a low energy beta emitter and the
body chemically handles it like water. While we do not know about the
dose, nor about the effect it is having on these people, it is likely
of low risk.

As with all ionizing radiation, exposure to tritium increases the risk
of developing cancer. However, because it emits very low energy
radiation and leaves the body relatively quickly, for a given amount
of activity ingested, tritium is one of the least dangerous
radionuclides. Since tritium is almost always found as water, it goes
directly into soft tissues and organs. The associated dose to these
tissues is generally uniform and dependent on the tissues' water
content.

A water cooler being contaminated certainly looks intentional. Surely
the investigation will reveal if this was intentional or if there was
some mishap that resulted in all bottled water being contaminated.

As tritium is generally handled as water, it is hopeful the affected
individuals did not receive a toxic dose and will be fine.

Portions of this comment have been extracted from
<http://www.epa.gov/rpdweb00/radionuclides/tritium.html> and from
<http://www.physics.isu.edu/radinf/tritium.htm> - Mod.TG]

[It is unclear when the incident happened. According to [1] on 24 Nov,
according to [4] on 23 and 24 Nov (and according to The Hindu, on 25
Nov), according to [3] on 28 Nov.
Kaiga, in Uttara Kannada district, west Karnataka state, can be
located via the HealthMap/ProMED-mail interactive map of India at
<http://healthmap.org/r/00*G>. - Sr.Tech.Ed.MJ]
